# Appendix L: Open Conjectures Toward Full Clay Compliance

This appendix states the four structural ingredients of the Jaffe--Witten
problem description (Clay Mathematics Institute, official problem
statement, §4) that go *beyond* the existence of a positive mass gap, in
the form of explicit conjectures, with an honest accounting of what is
rigorous, what is conditional, and what would be needed to close each.

The appendix is organised so that each section can be read independently.
The format mirrors the verification appendices H and K: a precise
statement, the rigorous portion, the open portion, and a sketch of what
additional work would close the gap.


---


## L.0 Scope and motivation

The Jaffe--Witten problem statement (§4 of the Clay official PDF)
requires, *in addition to* the existence of a positive mass gap, four
further structural ingredients of any candidate quantum Yang--Mills
theory:

1. **Local quantum field operators** in correspondence with the
   gauge-invariant local polynomials in the curvature, e.g.\
   $\mathrm{Tr}(F_{ij}F_{kl})(x)$.
2. **Short-distance match to perturbative asymptotic freedom**:
   correlation functions of those operators should agree at short
   distances with the predictions of asymptotic freedom and perturbative
   renormalisation theory.
3. **A stress-energy tensor** $T_{\mu\nu}(x)$ as an operator-valued
   distribution, gauge-invariant, symmetric, conserved, and reproducing
   the trace anomaly.
4. **An operator product expansion** with prescribed local singularities
   determined by asymptotic freedom.

The main body of the present paper proves the Wilson lattice mass gap
unconditionally (Section 4) and the continuum mass gap unconditionally
(Section 5; the K-uniform starting conditions (H1)--(H2) are discharged
in Appendix M, resolving the former Tier 1B question). The four
structural ingredients above are *not* established by the main body. In
this appendix we state each as an explicit conjecture (L.1--L.4),
identify which sub-statements are rigorous in the present construction
or in the existing literature, and identify which sub-statements are
genuinely open problems in 4D non-Abelian constructive QFT.

**This appendix is not a proof of any of these ingredients.** Each
conjecture below is, to the best of our knowledge, of comparable
difficulty to known unsolved problems in mathematical physics, and the
intellectually honest reading of our results is the conservative one
stated in §L.6. Any future closure of the four conjectures, partial or
complete, would constitute a separate research programme on top of the
mass-gap proof.

We adopt the standing convention of the preprint that $b_0 =
11N/(48\pi^2)$ is the one-loop $\mathrm{SU}(N)$ Yang--Mills coefficient,
$\beta(g) = -b_0\,g^3 + O(g^5)$, and $\Lambda$ denotes the
non-perturbative $\mathrm{SU}(N)$ scale parameter. The renormalised
coupling at scale $\mu$ is $g(\mu)$, with running governed by
$\beta(g)$ at one loop.


