## L.1 Renormalised composite operators (Conjecture L.1)


### L.1.1 Statement

**Conjecture L.1.** *There exist operator-valued distributions*
$$
[\mathrm{Tr}\,F^2]_R(x), \qquad
[\mathrm{Tr}(F_{\mu\rho}F_\nu{}^\rho)]_R(x), \qquad \ldots
$$
*on a common dense invariant domain $\mathcal{D} \subset \mathcal{H}$ of
the GNS Hilbert space reconstructed in §5.6, indexed by gauge-invariant
local polynomials in $F_{\mu\nu}$ and its covariant derivatives modulo
equation-of-motion redundancies, with the following properties:*

(i) *Each $[\mathcal{O}]_R$ is the limit, as $a \to 0$, of a
multiplicatively renormalised lattice operator,*
$$
[\mathcal{O}]_R(f) \;=\; \lim_{a \to 0}\;
Z_\mathcal{O}(a)\,\sum_{x \in \Lambda_a} a^4\,
\mathcal{O}^{\mathrm{bare}}_a(x)\,f(x),
\qquad f \in \mathcal{S}(\mathbb{R}^4),
$$
*where $\mathcal{O}^{\mathrm{bare}}_a$ is the natural lattice
representative (clover-improved $F^2$, smeared plaquette,
gradient-flow operator, etc.) and $Z_\mathcal{O}(a)$ is a
multiplicative renormalisation constant chosen so that the limit
exists as a tempered distribution;*

(ii) *The renormalised Schwinger functions $S_n^{\mathrm{ren}}$ are
finite tempered distributions on $(\mathbb{R}^4)^n$, smooth off the
total diagonal, satisfy OS positivity, Euclidean invariance, and
cluster decomposition;*

(iii) *The anomalous dimensions of the lowest-dimension scalar
composites match the one-loop perturbative QCD predictions; in
particular, by the Spiridonov--Chetyrkin trace-anomaly identity,*
$$
\gamma_{\mathrm{Tr}\,F^2}(g)
\;=\; -\,\frac{2\,\beta(g)}{g}
\;=\; -\,2\,b_0\,g^2 + O(g^4).
$$


### L.1.2 What is rigorous

The following ingredients are either standard or rigorously established
by inputs already used in the main body.

- **Bare lattice operator.** For $\mathcal{O} = \mathrm{Tr}\,F^2$, the
  symmetrised plaquette operator
  $$
  \mathcal{O}^{\mathrm{bare}}_a(x)
  \;:=\; \frac{2N}{a^4 g_0^2}\,\hat{s}_P(x),
  \qquad
  \hat{s}_P(x) := \frac{1}{6}\sum_{\mu < \nu}
  \bigl(1 - \tfrac{1}{N}\,\mathrm{Re}\,\mathrm{Tr}\,U_{P_{\mu\nu}}(x)\bigr),
  $$
  is gauge-invariant, hypercubic-covariant, and has classical continuum
  limit $\tfrac{1}{2}\,\mathrm{Tr}\,F^2(x) + O(a^2)$ by the standard
  plaquette expansion (preprint §5.2.1).

- **Trace-anomaly identity for $\gamma_O$.** The combination
  $(\beta(g)/g^3)\,\mathrm{Tr}\,F^2$ is renormalisation-group invariant
  to all orders in continuum perturbation theory (Spiridonov 1984;
  Spiridonov--Chetyrkin 1988). Equivalently, $\gamma_O = -2\beta(g)/g$
  is exact within continuum perturbation theory. This identity is the
  structural input that fixes the prefactor of any future
  $Z_{\mathrm{Tr}\,F^2}(a)$.

- **Lattice perturbative anomalous dimension.** The lattice
  Caracciolo--Curci--Menotti--Pelissetto programme (Phys. Lett. B 228
  (1989) 375; Nucl. Phys. B 375 (1992) 195; reviewed in Capitani,
  Phys. Rep. 382 (2003) 113) computes
  $\gamma_O(g) = -2\,b_0\,g^2 + O(g^4)$ for the symmetrised plaquette
  operator, with the same coefficient as the continuum result. Reisz's
  power-counting theorem (CMP 116 (1988) 81; CMP 117 (1988) 79) then
  guarantees lattice-to-continuum convergence of individual one-loop
  Feynman integrals up to $O(a^2 \log^k a)$ corrections.

- **Conditional GNS reconstruction.** Given (ii) of Conjecture L.1, the
  Osterwalder--Schrader reconstruction theorem applied to the
  renormalised Schwinger functions yields operator-valued distributions
  $[\mathcal{O}]_R(f)$ on a common invariant dense domain
  $\mathcal{D} \subset \mathcal{H}$. Since $Z_\mathcal{O}(a)$ is a
  positive scalar, OS positivity for $S_n^{\mathrm{ren}}$ reduces to
  OS positivity for the bare lattice Schwinger functions, which the
  preprint already establishes (modulo the Tier 1B K-uniform spectral
  lemma question of §5.5).


### L.1.3 What is open

- **Non-perturbative existence of the limit in (i).** For 4D
  non-Abelian Yang--Mills, neither
  $$
  \lim_{a \to 0}\,Z_\mathcal{O}(a)^2\,
  \bigl\langle\mathcal{O}^{\mathrm{bare}}_a(x)\,
  \mathcal{O}^{\mathrm{bare}}_a(y)\bigr\rangle_a
  $$
  nor its higher-point analogues are known to exist non-perturbatively
  as finite tempered distributions. The Symanzik composite-operator
  programme conjectures that $Z_\mathcal{O}(a)$, defined via the
  one-loop running formula $Z_\mathcal{O}(a) \sim
  (\log(1/a\Lambda))^{-\gamma_\mathcal{O}^{(0)}/(2 b_0)}$, absorbs
  all lattice divergences to all orders; this has been proved for
  super-renormalisable theories such as $\phi^4_3$ (Glimm--Jaffe), but
  not for marginal 4D non-Abelian gauge theory.

- **Operator mixing for higher-dimension composites.** Beyond
  dimension 4, scalar composites of the same quantum numbers mix under
  renormalisation, producing a renormalisation matrix rather than a
  scalar $Z_\mathcal{O}$. Even the *structure* of this mixing matrix is
  non-trivial in the non-perturbative regime; in particular, the
  Kluberg-Stern--Zuber theorem (Phys. Rev. D 12 (1975) 467) on the
  decoupling of equation-of-motion operators is a perturbative
  statement.

- **No existing precedent in 4D non-Abelian YM.** Hollands and Wald
  (CMP 223 (2001); CMP 231 (2002); CMP 293 (2010)) constructed
  renormalised Wick polynomials and OPEs for *free* fields on curved
  spacetimes, and extended the framework to interacting QFTs via
  formal perturbation theory (Hollands--Wald 2003, 2005); none of
  these results applies non-perturbatively to 4D non-Abelian gauge
  theory. Balaban (CMP 1984--1989), Magnen--Rivasseau--Sénéor (CMP
  155 (1993) 325), and Federbush (CMP 1987--1990) constructed the
  lattice-to-continuum limit of pure YM Schwinger functions in finite
  volume, but none constructed renormalised composite operators as
  distributions.


### L.1.4 What would close it

A non-perturbative construction of $[\mathrm{Tr}\,F^2]_R$ for 4D
non-Abelian YM would require:

- Adapting the Hollands--Wald local-covariant framework to a
  non-perturbative gauge-invariant setting, presumably via
  gradient-flow regularisation (Suzuki, PTEP 2013:083B03;
  Makino--Suzuki, PTEP 2014:063B02) which automatically smears
  composite operators over a Gaussian of width $\sqrt{8t}$ and
  renders them UV-finite at any flow time $t > 0$.
- Establishing convergence of $Z_\mathcal{O}(a)\,
  \mathcal{O}^{\mathrm{bare}}_a$ as $a \to 0$ (or, equivalently in the
  flow-time picture, the small-flow-time limit of the flowed
  composite) at the non-perturbative level — the genuine open
  problem.
- Demonstrating compatibility with the spectral and OS data already
  constructed in §5 of the main body.

This is the work of one or more original constructive-QFT papers,
independent of (and prerequisite to) the conjectures L.2--L.4 below.


