## L.2 Short-distance match to asymptotic freedom (Conjecture L.2)


### L.2.1 Statement

**Conjecture L.2.** *Conditional on Conjecture L.1, the renormalised
two-point Schwinger function of $[\mathrm{Tr}\,F^2]_R$ satisfies the
short-distance asymptotic*
$$
\bigl\langle\,[\mathrm{Tr}\,F^2]_R(x)\;[\mathrm{Tr}\,F^2]_R(0)\,\bigr\rangle
\;=\; \frac{C_N}{|x|^{8}}\;
\Bigl(\ln\frac{1}{|x|\Lambda}\Bigr)^{-2}
\bigl[1 + O\bigl((\log)^{-1}\bigr)\bigr]
\qquad (|x| \to 0),
$$
*with $C_N = 2(N^2-1)/\pi^6$ and $\Lambda$ the non-perturbative
$\mathrm{SU}(N)$ Lambda parameter. More generally, the renormalised
$n$-point Schwinger functions admit a short-distance asymptotic
expansion whose coefficients agree with those of continuum perturbative
QCD at leading order in $\alpha_s(1/|x|)$.*


### L.2.2 What is rigorous

- **Continuum perturbative result.** The one-loop continuum
  computation of $\langle\mathrm{Tr}\,F^2(x)\,\mathrm{Tr}\,F^2(0)\rangle$
  is textbook (Peskin--Schroeder Ch. 17; Collins, *Renormalization*,
  1984, Ch. 10--14; Muta, *Foundations of Perturbative QCD*, 1998,
  Ch. 5). Renormalisation-group improvement at $\mu = 1/|x|$, combined
  with the running of $\alpha_s$ and the trace-anomaly identity
  $\gamma_O = -2\beta(g)/g$, produces the displayed
  $|x|^{-8}(\log)^{-2}$ form with the explicit constant $C_N$. Three-loop
  Wilson coefficients are computed in Zoller--Chetyrkin, JHEP 12
  (2012) 119, and JHEP 10 (2014) 169.

- **Reisz lattice power counting.** Reisz's theorem (CMP 116 (1988)
  81; CMP 117 (1988) 79) establishes that one-loop lattice Feynman
  integrals built from a renormalisable lattice action converge to
  their continuum counterparts as $a \to 0$, with errors $O(a^2 \log^k
  a)$. Extended to lattice gauge theory by Lüscher--Weisz (CMP 97
  (1985) 59) and to gauge-invariant composites by Caracciolo--Curci--
  Menotti--Pelissetto (Phys. Lett. B 228 (1989) 375; Nucl. Phys. B 375
  (1992) 195). Reisz power counting is *purely perturbative*: it
  controls the agreement between lattice and continuum perturbation
  theory diagram-by-diagram, not the relation between non-perturbative
  Schwinger functions and their formal perturbation series.

- **Tree-level lattice match.** The leading short-distance power
  $|x|^{-8}$ — without the logarithmic correction — is recovered at
  *tree level* in lattice perturbation theory directly from the bare
  plaquette operator and the free lattice gluon propagator, using
  $\hat{s}_P = (a^4 g_0^2/(4N))\,\mathrm{Tr}\,F^2 + O(a^6)$ and the
  tree-level continuum Wick contraction. This establishes
  $$
  \lim_{a \to 0}\,
  \bigl\langle\mathcal{O}^{\mathrm{bare}}_a(x)\,
  \mathcal{O}^{\mathrm{bare}}_a(0)\bigr\rangle^{\mathrm{tree}}_{\mathrm{lat}}
  \;=\; \frac{2(N^2-1)}{\pi^4}\,\frac{\alpha_s^2}{|x|^8}
  \bigl[1 + O(a^2/|x|^2)\bigr],
  $$
  which already corrects the engineering-dimension power but does not
  yet contain the AF logarithm. No composite-operator renormalisation
  $Z_\mathcal{O}(a)$ enters at tree level.


### L.2.3 What is open

- **Non-perturbative = perturbative at short distances.** The standard
  hypothesis of QCD phenomenology — that the renormalised
  non-perturbative Schwinger function admits a short-distance
  asymptotic expansion whose coefficients coincide with the
  perturbative ones at leading order in $\alpha_s(1/|x|)$ — has never
  been rigorously proved for 4D non-Abelian gauge theory. It is
  implicitly assumed in every lattice QCD application of the OPE; it
  is a theorem in super-renormalisable cases such as $\phi^4_3$
  (Glimm--Jaffe; Magnen--Rivasseau--Sénéor); for 4D YM it is open.

- **Logarithmic correction.** The $(\log)^{-2}$ AF correction in the
  conjectured short-distance form requires both Conjecture L.1
  (existence of $Z_\mathcal{O}(a)$ at the non-perturbative level) and
  the standard non-perturbative-equals-perturbative hypothesis above.
  Neither is proved.


### L.2.4 What would close it

Conjecture L.2 reduces, modulo Conjecture L.1, to the standard
"OPE-in-QCD" hypothesis. A rigorous closure would either (i) establish
the QCD OPE hypothesis non-perturbatively for 4D YM as a separate
theorem — comparable in difficulty to constructing the theory itself —
or (ii) bypass the OPE by an alternative direct argument linking
renormalised Schwinger functions to their perturbative expansions at
short distances. Neither route is currently available.

It is fair to call Conjecture L.2 a "milder" residual gap than L.1: if
L.1 is closed, then L.2 reduces to invoking a single standard but
unproved hypothesis. By contrast, L.1 is the substantive constructive
problem.


