## L.3 Stress-energy tensor (Conjecture L.3)


### L.3.1 Statement

**Conjecture L.3.** *Conditional on Conjecture L.1, the
Belinfante--Rosenfeld improved stress tensor*
$$
T_{\mu\nu}(x)
\;:=\; -\,[\mathrm{Tr}(F_{\mu\rho}F_\nu{}^\rho)]_R(x)
\;+\; \tfrac{1}{4}\,\delta_{\mu\nu}\,[\mathrm{Tr}\,F^2]_R(x)
\;+\; c_{\mathrm{vac}}\,\delta_{\mu\nu}\,\mathbb{1}
$$
*exists as an operator-valued distribution on the GNS Hilbert space
$\mathcal{H}$ of §5.6, with $c_{\mathrm{vac}}$ chosen so that
$\langle\Omega\,|\,T_{\mu\nu}(f)\,|\,\Omega\rangle = 0$ for all
$f \in \mathcal{S}(\mathbb{R}^4)$, and satisfies:*

(i) *Symmetry $T_{\mu\nu} = T_{\nu\mu}$;*

(ii) *Gauge invariance, inherited from Conjecture L.1;*

(iii) *Conservation as a distributional Ward identity:*
$\partial^\mu T_{\mu\nu}(x) = 0$ *as a distributional identity, with
contact terms encoding translation covariance;*

(iv) *Operator-level identification of the OS Hamiltonian:*
$$
H_{\mathrm{OS}} \;=\; \int T_{00}(0,\vec x)\,d^3\vec x
$$
*with $H_{\mathrm{OS}} \geq 0$ and $H_{\mathrm{OS}}\,\Omega = 0$;*

(v) *Trace anomaly as an exact operator identity:*
$$
T^\mu{}_\mu(x)
\;=\; \frac{\beta(g)}{2\,g}\,[\mathrm{Tr}\,F^2]_R(x).
$$


### L.3.2 What is rigorous (unconditionally)

Two of the operator-theoretic requirements above are *unconditionally*
established by the main body and standard lattice constructive QFT,
independently of Conjecture L.1.

- **Positivity of the energy.** The OS Hamiltonian
  $H_{\mathrm{OS}} = -a^{-1}\log T_{\mathrm{transf}}$ from the
  reconstructed transfer matrix satisfies $H_{\mathrm{OS}} \geq 0$
  with $H_{\mathrm{OS}}\,\Omega = 0$. This follows from OS3
  (reflection positivity) plus the standard Osterwalder--Seiler
  argument (Seiler 1982, *Lecture Notes in Physics* 159), invoked in
  §5.6 of the main body. It does *not* depend on the existence of any
  composite operator on $\mathcal{H}$.

- **Conservation as a distributional Ward identity (bulk).** The
  Schwinger--Dyson identity established in §5.7(f) of the main body
  reads, for an observable $X$ supported away from $x$,
  $$
  \partial_x^\mu \,\bigl\langle T_{\mu\nu}(x)\,X\bigr\rangle
  \;=\; \sum_i \delta^{(4)}(x - x_i)\,\partial_{\nu, x_i}\langle X\rangle
  \;+\; (\text{trace-anomaly contact terms}),
  $$
  where the bulk term gives $\partial^\mu T_{\mu\nu} = 0$ as a
  distributional identity in any region disjoint from the support of
  $X$. This is the exact lattice/continuum translation Ward identity
  of §5.7(f); it is a statement about Schwinger functions, derivable
  without invoking composite operators on $\mathcal{H}$.

- **Classical Belinfante--Rosenfeld improvement.** The classical step
  $$
  T^{\mathrm{can}}_{\mu\nu} \;\longrightarrow\;
  T^{\mathrm{imp}}_{\mu\nu}
  \;=\; -F^a_{\mu\rho}\,F^{a\,\rho}_\nu
  \;+\; \tfrac{1}{4}\,\delta_{\mu\nu}\,F^a_{\rho\sigma}\,F^{a\,\rho\sigma}
  $$
  is a textbook computation (Belinfante 1939; Rosenfeld 1940;
  Gotay--Marsden 1992); the improved tensor is gauge-invariant,
  symmetric, traceless on shell, and conserved on shell. Lattice
  versions via the clover field strength are constructed in
  Caracciolo--Curci--Menotti--Pelissetto, Ann. Phys. 197 (1990) 119,
  and via the Yang--Mills gradient flow in Suzuki, PTEP 2013:083B03,
  and Makino--Suzuki, PTEP 2014:063B02.


### L.3.3 What is open

- **Operator-level identification (iv).** The identification
  $H_{\mathrm{OS}} = \int T_{00}\,d^3\vec x$ as an *operator equation*
  on $\mathcal{D} \subset \mathcal{H}$ requires both (a) Conjecture
  L.1, so that $T_{00}$ exists as an operator-valued distribution, and
  (b) verification that the integrated zero-zero component coincides
  with the OS Hamiltonian.

- **Trace anomaly as exact operator identity (v).** Collins--Duncan--
  Joglekar (Phys. Rev. D 16 (1977) 438) and the Spiridonov--Chetyrkin
  identity establish (v) at the level of continuum perturbation
  theory. Promoting it to an exact operator identity on $\mathcal{H}$
  is conditional on Conjecture L.1 and a non-perturbative
  composite-operator calculus in the spirit of Hollands--Wald.

- **Bulk-to-everywhere upgrade of (iii).** The conservation Ward
  identity is rigorous as a statement about Schwinger functions; the
  full distributional identity $\partial^\mu T_{\mu\nu}(x) = 0$ as an
  identity *between operator-valued distributions* on $\mathcal{H}$
  requires the same composite-operator infrastructure as (iv) and (v).


### L.3.4 What would close it

Conditional on Conjecture L.1, the residual obstructions to L.3 are
considerably weaker than L.1 itself. Specifically:

- The Suzuki / Makino--Suzuki gradient-flow construction provides a
  UV-automatically-finite regularisation of the stress tensor via two
  perturbatively matched coefficients $c_1(t), c_2(t)$, and Del
  Debbio--Patella--Rago (JHEP 11 (2013) 212) derived the Ward
  identities fixing them. This is the cleanest available *lattice*
  construction. Promoting the small-flow-time limit $t \to 0^+$ to a
  non-perturbative operator-valued distribution is the residual hard
  step, of difficulty comparable to (but not beyond) Conjecture L.1.

- Estimated effort: 2--3 months of focused follow-up work,
  conditional on L.1. The classical Belinfante--Rosenfeld improvement
  is unambiguous; the lattice machinery is in place; the trace anomaly
  is fixed by the same Spiridonov identity used in L.1.iii; the
  Hamiltonian positivity is independent of all composite-operator
  conjectures. The non-trivial residual is the operator-level
  identification, which is technically downstream of L.1.

In short, if L.1 is granted, L.3 is the *easiest* of the four Clay
structural ingredients.


