## L.4 Operator product expansion (Conjecture L.4)


### L.4.1 Statement

**Conjecture L.4 (leading-order OPE).** *Conditional on Conjectures
L.1 and L.2, the renormalised composite operators $[\mathrm{Tr}\,F^2]_R$
admit a leading-order operator product expansion as
$|x - y| \to 0$:*
$$
[\mathrm{Tr}\,F^2]_R(x)\;[\mathrm{Tr}\,F^2]_R(y)
\;\sim\; C^{\mathbb{1}}(x - y)\,\mathbb{1}
\;+\; C^{\mathcal{O}}(x - y)\,[\mathrm{Tr}\,F^2]_R(y)
\;+\; \sum_{k:\,d_k \geq 6} C^{k}(x - y)\,\mathcal{O}_k(y),
$$
*with c-number tempered distributions $C^k$ smooth off the diagonal,
the identity-channel coefficient given by*
$$
C^{\mathbb{1}}(x - y)
\;=\; \frac{C_N}{|x - y|^{8}}\,
\Bigl(\ln\frac{1}{|x - y|\,\Lambda}\Bigr)^{-2}\,
\bigl[1 + O\bigl((\log)^{-1}\bigr)\bigr],
\qquad C_N \;=\; \frac{2(N^2 - 1)}{\pi^6},
$$
*and subleading channels with strictly weaker singular behaviour at
coincidence. The complete operator basis $\{\mathcal{O}_k\}$ ordered by
scaling dimension consists of gauge-invariant local polynomials in
$F_{\mu\nu}$ and its covariant derivatives modulo equation-of-motion
redundancies (Kluberg-Stern--Zuber).*


### L.4.2 What is rigorous

- **Coincident-point bound on $S_n$.** The Källén--Lehmann derivation
  of §5.7(f) of the main body (introduced as the Tier 2 F1 fix to the
  Local Integrability lemma) establishes the coincident-point bound
  $$
  |S_n(x_1, \ldots, x_n)|
  \;\leq\; C^n\,n!\,
  \prod_{i < j}(1 + |x_i - x_j|^{-2})\,e^{-\Delta\,\mathrm{diam}}
  $$
  *without* invoking any operator product expansion, relying instead
  on Källén--Lehmann applied to each connected two-point function, the
  mass gap $\Delta > 0$, the linked-cluster theorem, and Glimm--Jaffe
  (Theorem 8.4.3) iteration along a spanning tree. This bound is
  unconditionally rigorous and is sufficient for OS0' local
  integrability and the OS-axiom verification of §5.6.

- **Perturbative leading coefficients.** The identity-channel
  coefficient $C^{\mathbb{1}}$ at leading order in $\alpha_s(1/|x|)$
  is the same object that appears in Conjecture L.2 and is computed
  to three loops in Zoller--Chetyrkin (JHEP 12 (2012) 119; JHEP 10
  (2014) 169) and at the level of phenomenological sum rules in
  Shifman--Vainshtein--Zakharov (Nucl. Phys. B 147 (1979) 385, 448)
  and Novikov--Shifman--Vainshtein--Zakharov (Nucl. Phys. B 249 (1985)
  445). The structural form of the OPE in perturbative QFT is
  established by Wilson--Zimmermann (CMP 24 (1972) 87), Zimmermann
  ("Normal products" (1973)), and the rigorous distributional version
  by Hollands (CMP 273 (2007) 1) and Hollands--Wald (CMP 293 (2010)
  85).

- **Local operator basis at low dimension.** Modulo equation-of-motion
  redundancies and $\mathcal{C}$-parity selection rules, the
  gauge-invariant scalar local operators in pure 4D YM up to dimension
  6 form a finite list:
  $\mathbb{1}$,
  $[\mathrm{Tr}\,F^2]_R$,
  $[\mathrm{Tr}\,F\tilde F]_R$ ($\mathcal{C}$-odd, decoupled),
  $[\mathrm{Tr}(D_\rho F_{\mu\nu})^2]_R$.
  This classification (Kluberg-Stern--Zuber, Phys. Rev. D 12 (1975)
  467) is a rigorous structural fact at the level of formal
  composites; existence of the listed operators on $\mathcal{H}$
  remains conditional on Conjecture L.1.


### L.4.3 What is open

- **The OPE structure itself.** A non-perturbative operator product
  expansion for 4D non-Abelian Yang--Mills — namely a system of
  c-number distributions $\{C^k\}$ such that the asymptotic identity
  above holds at the level of *operators* on $\mathcal{H}$ — has never
  been constructed. Hollands--Wald's perturbative OPE for free and
  interacting QFTs on curved spacetimes does not extend to the 4D
  non-Abelian gauge case; Bostelmann's phase-space approach
  (J. Math. Phys. 46 (2005) 082304) presupposes a phase-space
  nuclearity axiom not proved for 4D YM.

- **Non-perturbative identification of $C^k$.** Even granting
  existence of the OPE structure, the identification of the
  non-perturbative coefficients $C^k$ with their perturbative
  counterparts is the same hypothesis as Conjecture L.2 (the standard
  "OPE-in-QCD" hypothesis), which is open.

- **Mixing matrices at dimension $\geq 6$.** Operator mixing for
  scalar composites of dimension $\geq 6$ produces a renormalisation
  *matrix*, whose explicit structure is unknown non-perturbatively
  even in principle.


### L.4.4 What would close it

A rigorous non-perturbative OPE for 4D non-Abelian YM is, to the best
of our knowledge, of comparable difficulty to constructing the theory
itself. A serious attempt would have to combine: (i) a non-perturbative
analogue of the Hollands--Wald local-covariant framework for composite
operators on curved spacetime (Conjecture L.1); (ii) a rigorous
verification of the QCD OPE hypothesis at short distances (the content
of Conjecture L.2 promoted to all channels); (iii) explicit control of
the dimension-$\geq 6$ mixing matrices. Of the four conjectures L.1--L.4,
this is the hardest residual problem.

The intellectually honest restricted version is the *leading-order*
statement above: the dominant short-distance singularity of the
identity channel is $|x|^{-8}(\log)^{-2}$, with the explicit constant
$C_N$. Under a charitable reading of "prescribed local singularities
predicted by asymptotic freedom" — *the* dominant singularity, with its
AF logarithm — this is the maximum the present state of the art
supports.


### L.4.5 Distinction from the §5.7(f) coincident-point bound

The coincident-point bound on $S_n$ established in §5.7(f) of the main
body (the Tier 2 F1 fix) and Conjecture L.4 address logically *distinct*
clauses of the Jaffe--Witten requirements. We highlight the distinction
to avoid any misreading.

| Item | §5.7(f) F1 fix | Conjecture L.4 |
|:-----|:---------------|:----------------|
| Bound on $S_n$ at coincident points | **Proved** (Källén--Lehmann + linked cluster) | Not the target |
| OS0' local integrability | **Proved** | Not relevant |
| OS-axiom verification of §5.6 | **Closed** | Not needed |
| Existence of an OPE *as structure* of the theory | Not addressed | **Open** |
| AF-corrected leading short-distance singularity | Not addressed | **Open / leading-order conjecture** |
| Jaffe--Witten "OPE with prescribed singularities" clause | **Not met** by F1 alone | Target, met only via the leading-order conjecture above |

The §5.7(f) F1 fix removes the *logical dependence* of the OS-axiom
verification on the existence of an OPE: the local integrability lemma
required for OS0' is now derived from spectral and cluster estimates
alone, with no reference to the OPE. What it does *not* do is provide
the OPE structure that the Jaffe--Witten problem statement separately
demands. Conjecture L.4 is therefore logically independent of the F1
fix, and the F1 fix in no way reduces the burden of L.4.


---


## L.5 Logical relationship between Conjectures L.1--L.4

The four conjectures are not independent. Their logical structure is:

```
                       L.1
                  (composites)
                  /     |     \
                 v      v      v
               L.2    L.3    L.4
              (AF)  (T_mu_nu)  (OPE)
```

- **L.1** (renormalised composite operators) is the foundational
  conjecture: it asserts the existence of the operator-valued
  distributions on which L.2--L.4 depend. Closure of L.1 alone would
  unlock all three downstream items conditionally.

- **L.2** (AF short-distance match) reduces, conditional on L.1, to
  invoking the standard non-perturbative-equals-perturbative
  hypothesis of QCD phenomenology. It is the "mildest" residual gap
  in the sense that the additional conjectural input beyond L.1 is a
  single standard hypothesis ubiquitous in lattice QCD applications.

- **L.3** (stress-energy tensor) is, conditional on L.1, closeable in
  estimated 2--3 months via the Suzuki / Makino--Suzuki gradient-flow
  construction. Crucially, two of its sub-clauses are
  *unconditionally* rigorous: positivity of the OS Hamiltonian
  $H_{\mathrm{OS}} \geq 0$, and the conservation Ward identity at the
  level of Schwinger functions. The residual obstructions
  (operator-level identification, exact trace-anomaly identity)
  reduce to standard composite-operator calculus once L.1 is granted.

- **L.4** (operator product expansion) is the hardest residual
  problem and remains open even granted L.1, L.2, L.3. The
  *leading-order* conjecture is the most one can responsibly state;
  the full channel decomposition with non-perturbative identification
  of all coefficients is, to the best of our knowledge, comparable in
  difficulty to constructing the theory itself.

The natural ordering for any future research programme is therefore
L.1 first, then L.3 (cheap follow-up), then L.2 (a standard hypothesis
once L.1 is granted), and finally L.4 (open at full strength,
leading-order accessible).

We emphasise once more that *none* of the above is a proof or a
proposed proof: it is a status assessment of four standing open
problems, organised so that future workers can identify which
sub-conjecture they are attacking and what they would need to invoke.


